25/05/2003
OHRID, Macedonia -- The leaders of several countries in the Balkans agreed Friday (23 May) to boost security along the borders of their countries in order to fight trafficking and organised crime.Meeting at a conference organised by NATO, the EU and the OSCE, they agreed to implement better surveillance and border police training, set up a joint database on crime, and share more information. 
They also thanked the EU for setting aside $125m for boosting border security in the region. 
The conference was attended by leaders from Serbia-Montenegro, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, Albania and Bulgaria, as well as UN officials from Kosovo. 
(AP - 23/05/03)
